WEBVTT

00:00.642 --> 00:03.885
Well, who's your fans since the last time we gathered?

00:04.786 --> 00:06.928
IU won the national championship.

00:07.769 --> 00:09.030
That's a pretty great moment.

00:09.390 --> 00:10.271
Congratulations.

00:12.293 --> 00:14.555
It's also divisional round weekend in the NFL.

00:14.675 --> 00:20.301
And if you're here today online, you already know we got snowed in too.

00:21.082 --> 00:29.970
And like many of you, I've been watching all of this unfold from a bit of a distance as far as football goes because my favorite team in the plane.

00:30.626 --> 00:40.761
We're not even in the championship conversation this year and haven't been for a minute, but something unexpected and really meaningful caught my attention over the last few weeks.

00:41.942 --> 00:44.847
The Bengals fan community is a pretty tight knit group.

00:45.327 --> 00:49.714
There's a lot of interaction between fans and the journalists who cover the team.

00:50.435 --> 00:58.226
And recently one of those longtime reporters experienced a sudden and devastating loss, the unexpected death of his spouse.

00:59.554 --> 01:06.103
And in response, fellow journalists set up a GoFundMe to help cover the financial burden the family was facing.

01:06.124 --> 01:10.630
And almost immediately the response from the fan community was overwhelming.

01:10.670 --> 01:21.766
Messages of support, stories of gratitude, generosity pouring in from people who didn't have to do anything but they just wanted to.

01:21.786 --> 01:27.154
And I found myself watching that unfold and I felt something stirring in me too.

01:27.970 --> 01:30.253
I wish I could say that I jumped in right away, but it didn't.

01:31.535 --> 01:39.747
What moved me was seeing how much good was happening, seeing people show up, seeing kindness ripple outward.

01:40.027 --> 01:46.476
And eventually I wanted to be part of that too, even if it was just a small gift and in a small way.

01:46.496 --> 01:49.801
And it reminded me of something important.

01:50.883 --> 01:56.050
There's a kind of generosity that doesn't come from pressure, comes from joy.

01:57.058 --> 02:02.566
From belonging, from seeing something good and wanting to help it continue.

02:04.088 --> 02:13.021
There's something life giving about being part of something bigger than yourself, about participating in care, hope and restoration.

02:14.523 --> 02:17.989
And what struck me is that none of that generosity had to be forced.

02:19.010 --> 02:24.498
Grace was already at work and people simply responded to it.

02:25.826 --> 02:27.729
And that's actually what brings us to today.

02:27.789 --> 02:31.936
But we're in the final week of our series, The Generous Light.

02:31.996 --> 02:39.609
And today we're going to look at two passages in Second Corinthians that speak directly to why Christians give.

02:39.649 --> 02:52.370
And what we'll see is that God doesn't call us to generosity through obligation or compulsion, but he invites us into generosity through grace, through joy.

02:53.666 --> 03:00.676
through a desire to see his work, not just survive, but to thrive in the world.

03:00.736 --> 03:13.994
And that instinct to respond freely to grace rather than pressure is exactly what Paul points to when he begins talking about generosity in the early church.

03:14.715 --> 03:17.739
So our first passage, I'm gonna break this up into four smaller sections.

03:18.099 --> 03:22.866
It's gonna be in 2 Corinthians 8, 1, 3, 4, and this is what all writes.

03:23.234 --> 03:31.045
He says, we want you to know brothers and sisters about the grace of God that was given to the churches of Macedonia.

03:31.086 --> 03:42.863
During a severe trial brought about by affliction, their abundant joy and their extreme poverty overflowed in a wealth of generosity on their part.

03:42.883 --> 03:50.514
I can testify that according to their ability and even beyond their ability of their own accord,

03:51.138 --> 03:56.425
They begged us earnestly for the privilege of sharing in the ministry to the saints.

03:58.028 --> 04:00.792
Now, Paul opens this section in a surprising way.

04:01.453 --> 04:04.417
He does an issue of command and he doesn't apply pressure.

04:04.437 --> 04:09.504
Instead, he tells a story about the churches in Macedonia.

04:09.544 --> 04:19.538
And it's not a success story by worldly standards, at least, because Paul describes them as experiencing severe affliction.

04:19.842 --> 04:24.707
and extreme poverty, language that literally means rock bottom poverty.

04:24.747 --> 04:27.710
These were not churches with margin.

04:28.271 --> 04:37.620
They were communities under pressure, likely facing persecution, social exclusion, and even economic hardship because of their faith.

04:38.781 --> 04:40.003
And yet Paul says this.

04:40.463 --> 04:47.090
He says, their abundant joy and their extreme poverty overflowed in a wealth of generosity.

04:47.714 --> 04:50.398
And that sentence should stop us in our tracks.

04:51.500 --> 04:54.165
Joy does not normally flow from affliction.

04:55.226 --> 05:00.856
Generosity does not normally flow from poverty, unless something else is at work.

05:02.018 --> 05:04.402
And Paul's careful to name what that something is.

05:05.003 --> 05:09.229
He doesn't credit personality, temperament, or strong leadership.

05:09.610 --> 05:14.418
He says this generosity came from the grace of God that was given to them.

05:14.850 --> 05:17.853
And grace didn't wait until their circumstances improved.

05:18.594 --> 05:27.883
Grace met them in their hardship and grace empowered them to give beyond their ability voluntarily, even urgently.

05:27.923 --> 05:33.208
And Paul says they begged for the privilege of participating.

05:33.248 --> 05:35.610
And that word matters here.

05:35.950 --> 05:37.152
Just think about it for a minute.

05:37.852 --> 05:43.698
He uses the word privilege for the Macedonians, giving wasn't an obligation to fulfill.

05:44.130 --> 05:45.913
It was a grace to participate in.

05:46.393 --> 05:50.019
Their joy wasn't tied to what they had because they didn't really have anything.

05:50.459 --> 05:54.445
It was tied to being caught up in what God was doing.

05:55.427 --> 05:57.871
And Paul's already reframing generosity.

05:58.371 --> 06:00.515
Giving doesn't flow from abundance.

06:01.216 --> 06:02.277
It flows from grace.

06:03.118 --> 06:09.828
And when grace takes root, it produces a generosity that circumstances the loan cannot explain.

06:10.910 --> 06:13.554
So grace in Paul's language isn't a feeling

06:13.730 --> 06:19.780
It's God actively supplying what his people need to participate in what he is doing.

06:19.800 --> 06:26.150
Now he picks up the idea in 2 Corinthians 8, 5, or 9.

06:26.190 --> 06:29.275
So let's continue on in Paul's logic here.

06:29.936 --> 06:38.670
He writes, and not just as we had hoped, instead they gave themselves first to the Lord and then to us by God's will.

06:39.472 --> 06:40.914
So we urge Titus

06:41.218 --> 06:48.045
that just as he had begun, so he should also complete among you this act of grace.

06:49.006 --> 07:00.879
Now, as you excel in everything, in faith, speech, knowledge, and in all diligence, and in your love for us, excel also in this act of grace.

07:01.840 --> 07:10.610
I am not saying this as a command, rather by means of diligence of others, I am testing the genuineness of your love.

07:11.106 --> 07:19.015
For you know that the grace of our Lord Jesus Christ, though he was rich, or you're sick, he became poor.

07:19.615 --> 07:23.780
So that by his poverty, you might become rich.

07:25.482 --> 07:28.905
So Paul then tells us why the Macedonians gave the way that they did.

07:28.945 --> 07:33.250
And he says something subtle, but decisive.

07:34.652 --> 07:40.658
He says that they gave themselves first to the Lord and then to us by the will of God.

07:40.962 --> 07:41.663
And that's the key.

07:41.883 --> 07:43.665
Their generosity didn't start with money.

07:44.606 --> 07:45.667
It started with surrender.

07:46.188 --> 07:48.310
Their resources followed their devotion.

07:49.091 --> 07:52.615
And then Paul grounds the entire appeal in the gospel itself.

07:53.336 --> 07:56.660
He doesn't say give because others have less.

07:57.280 --> 08:04.889
He says, and just in case the Corinthians or we start thinking, this is about heroic believers, Paul immediately takes us somewhere deeper.

08:05.229 --> 08:09.554
He says, for you know the grace of our Lord Jesus Christ.

08:09.986 --> 08:17.976
Though he was rich, yet for your sake, he became poor so that you by his poverty might become rich.

08:18.537 --> 08:20.799
This is the theological center of the passage.

08:21.480 --> 08:24.444
Paul doesn't motivate giving through guilt or comparison.

08:24.965 --> 08:29.070
He motivates it through this theology word called Christology.

08:29.110 --> 08:39.122
And Paul here has a very high Christology because Jesus is the ultimate model of generosity, not because he gave something, but because he gave himself.

08:39.970 --> 08:43.455
The inequality that Paul points to is intentional.

08:44.016 --> 08:49.082
Whatever the Corinthians might give, it will never rival what Christ has already given.

08:49.723 --> 08:52.908
Grace always precedes generosity.

08:53.649 --> 08:55.471
So Paul isn't commanding them to give.

08:55.531 --> 08:58.776
He says he's testing the sincerity of their love.

09:00.057 --> 09:04.864
Not to shame them, but to see whether grace has truly taken root.

09:05.845 --> 09:09.330
Christian generosity and Paul's framework is never coerced.

09:10.050 --> 09:11.552
It's always a response.

09:12.312 --> 09:14.635
Grace received becomes grace embodied.

09:16.997 --> 09:22.103
So moving ahead, the second Corinthians nine, six through seven, then Paul writes this.

09:22.163 --> 09:27.188
He says, the point is this, the person who's so sparingly will also reap sparingly.

09:27.228 --> 09:32.113
And the person who's so generously will also reap generously.

09:32.133 --> 09:36.498
Each person should do as he has decided in his part,

09:36.898 --> 09:43.004
not reluctantly or out of compulsion, since God loves a cheerful giver.

09:43.965 --> 09:47.028
So in chapter nine, Paul returns to the heart behind the gift.

09:47.688 --> 09:53.694
He uses a familiar agricultural image, sewing and reaping, but this is not a prosperity formula.

09:54.054 --> 09:58.399
Paul is not promising that financial giving will result in financial gain.

09:59.380 --> 10:01.702
Instead, he reframes abundance itself.

10:02.162 --> 10:06.066
He makes us think about what it means to have abundance.

10:06.274 --> 10:07.436
and to give abundantly.

10:07.776 --> 10:13.905
He says, each person is to give what they have decided in their heart, not reluctantly or under compulsion.

10:13.985 --> 10:14.285
Why?

10:14.325 --> 10:17.149
Because God loves a cheerful giver.

10:17.690 --> 10:20.154
And that doesn't mean that God loves cheerful people more.

10:20.194 --> 10:25.661
It means God delights in generosity that grows out of freedom rather than fear.

10:26.563 --> 10:28.325
And that matters very deeply to us.

10:29.066 --> 10:34.674
Because Paul explicitly rejects manipulation, giving that flows from pressure

10:34.882 --> 10:36.685
misses the point altogether.

10:36.725 --> 10:43.836
The issue is not how much is given, but how it is given willingly, joyfully, freely.

10:45.258 --> 10:48.463
And even here, Paul grounds generosity in grace.

10:49.244 --> 10:52.049
The ability to give does not originate in the giver.

10:52.529 --> 10:53.731
It originates in God.

10:54.452 --> 10:56.235
Cheerfulness isn't manufactured.

10:56.716 --> 11:00.722
It flows from trust that God is already at work.

11:01.730 --> 11:07.337
This is sufficiency theology, not prosperity, theology or prosperity gospel.

11:08.158 --> 11:15.327
God supplies enough so that generosity can continue, not so that wealth can accumulate without purpose.

11:18.130 --> 11:24.778
And lastly, Paul writes in 2 Corinthians 9, 8 through 12 in our last section here.

11:25.559 --> 11:30.866
He says, and God is able to make every grace overflow to you so that in every way,

11:31.106 --> 11:35.752
always having everything you need, you may excel in every good work.

11:37.233 --> 11:39.536
As it is written, he distributed freely.

11:39.636 --> 11:42.860
He gave to the poor his righteousness endures forever.

11:43.801 --> 11:52.532
Now, the one who provides seed for the sower and bread for food will also provide and multiply your seed and increase the harvest of your righteousness.

11:54.054 --> 12:00.882
You will be enriched in every way for all generosity, which produces thanksgiving to God through us.

12:01.314 --> 12:10.932
The ministry of this service is not only supplying the needs of the saints, but is also overflowing in many expressions of thanks to God.

12:12.515 --> 12:15.100
So Paul closes where we begin with grace.

12:16.102 --> 12:19.108
He says, God is able to make every grace overflow to you.

12:19.389 --> 12:24.338
Notice the direction grace flows to believers and then through believers.

12:24.418 --> 12:31.128
God provides seed to the sower and bread for food, and he multiplies that seed so that righteousness increases.

12:31.709 --> 12:35.274
The result is not self-congratulation, it's Thanksgiving to God.

12:36.055 --> 12:40.642
Paul insists that generosity is never merely a financial transaction.

12:40.682 --> 12:42.665
It is a theological event.

12:43.326 --> 12:51.858
God receives the glory because God is the source, and giving becomes participation in God's own generous character.

12:52.450 --> 12:54.973
And Paul even anchors this in Israel's story.

12:55.814 --> 13:01.401
He's echoing the manna and the wilderness where no one had too much and no one had too little.

13:01.761 --> 13:05.846
God's provision created a community shaped by trust, not ordering.

13:06.687 --> 13:19.442
And that's Paul's vision for the church, not that the wealthy become poor, but that no one is left without care, not that generosity is heroic, but that it is normal in a grace formed community.

13:20.322 --> 13:29.736
A community where grace moves so freely that needs are met quietly, dignity is preserved, and God, not the giver, gets the credit.

13:30.577 --> 13:39.891
And when Paul finishes, we see this full circle, grace initiates the process and grace sustains it, and then grace completes the process.

13:40.172 --> 13:43.396
Generosity is not something Christians try harder to do.

13:43.436 --> 13:46.401
It's something grace forms us to become.

13:46.461 --> 13:49.906
And that's why our bottom line today is this.

13:49.986 --> 13:56.876
Grace receives always becomes grace given, not perfectly, not uniformly, but genuinely.

13:57.557 --> 13:59.941
And when it does, God's character is reflected.

14:00.602 --> 14:04.368
God's people are cared for and God receives the glory.

14:05.229 --> 14:11.418
So before we rush to what we should do with this, we need to pause and ask what it's revealing about us.

14:12.400 --> 14:14.643
Grace doesn't expose our hearts to shame us.

14:15.124 --> 14:16.646
It exposes them to heal us.

14:17.547 --> 14:19.250
Most of us don't cling to what

14:19.554 --> 14:20.935
We have because we're greedy.

14:21.516 --> 14:22.897
We cling because we're afraid.

14:22.957 --> 14:24.959
Afraid there won't be enough.

14:25.620 --> 14:26.941
Afraid we won't be okay.

14:27.502 --> 14:30.685
Afraid that if we loosen our grip, something will fall apart.

14:31.786 --> 14:41.655
When Paul's reminding us that generosity isn't about proving anything to God, it's about discovering where we're already trusting Him and where we're still learning to.

14:42.456 --> 14:46.480
So the question isn't how much should I give, as we've said throughout this series.

14:47.021 --> 14:48.562
The deeper question is,

14:48.866 --> 14:51.049
What grace have I already received?

14:51.629 --> 14:53.612
And what is that grace forming in me?

14:53.672 --> 15:04.625
And wherever that question lands for you today, eager, hesitant, maybe a little anxious, maybe even unsure, there's room for you here in this story.

15:06.307 --> 15:14.037
So to conclude, one of the things that stayed with me as I've sat with these passages is how little pressure there is in the way that Jesus gives.

15:14.798 --> 15:18.482
Notice he never coarses, he never shames, he never demands

15:18.658 --> 15:21.741
before he offers himself for us.

15:23.143 --> 15:33.634
Paul says, though he was rich, yet for your sake, he became poor, not because we were generous, not because we were faithful, but because he trusted the Father.

15:34.935 --> 15:40.561
And because he loved us, and that does something to me personally, I don't know about you.

15:41.302 --> 15:45.426
Because if I'm honest, there are moments when I look at generosity and others,

15:46.146 --> 15:48.528
and say, man, I wish I were more like that.

15:48.548 --> 15:53.814
I see the need, I feel that pull, but I also feel the limits.

15:54.374 --> 16:02.903
I feel the tight margins that we're all facing in this day and age and that quiet anxiety that says, what if I give and it's not enough?

16:04.264 --> 16:09.950
And when I keep realizing is this, God has been patient with me in this realm of life.

16:10.730 --> 16:11.611
He hasn't rushed me.

16:11.671 --> 16:14.514
He hasn't demanded I start at the highest level.

16:14.594 --> 16:18.858
He simply invited me to stay present and to keep trusting him.

16:18.898 --> 16:21.080
That's what grace does.

16:21.861 --> 16:24.624
Grace doesn't start by asking how much can I give?

16:24.684 --> 16:28.528
Grace starts by saying, come and receive.

16:29.649 --> 16:36.636
And when we receive it slowly and perfectly and honestly, it begins to change what we want.

16:37.537 --> 16:39.158
It reshapes our desires.

16:39.879 --> 16:42.802
It creates room where their wants was fear.

16:43.394 --> 16:48.322
That's why Paul can say grace received becomes grace given.

16:48.342 --> 16:56.575
And this week, that may simply mean staying open to grace, trusting that when God supplies it, generosity will follow.

16:56.615 --> 17:01.322
Not all at once, not always dramatically, but genuinely.

17:01.342 --> 17:08.914
And I think that's especially important for those of you who are like me and are quietly anxious right now.

17:09.410 --> 17:12.194
Those who want to be faithful but feel stretched in.

17:12.234 --> 17:16.199
Those who worry that what you have won't matter or won't be enough.

17:17.140 --> 17:18.321
Here's the good news.

17:19.263 --> 17:21.465
God does not ask you to be impressive.

17:22.206 --> 17:24.409
He does not ask you to be the best.

17:25.170 --> 17:28.554
He does not ask you to give what you do not have.

17:29.395 --> 17:30.997
He asks for your presence.

17:31.999 --> 17:33.200
He asks for your care.

17:33.981 --> 17:35.503
He asks for your trust.

17:36.104 --> 17:37.746
Because when Jesus looks at us,

17:38.146 --> 17:40.349
He's not first asking how much did you give?

17:40.369 --> 17:42.913
He's asking, will you walk with me here?

17:44.375 --> 17:56.732
And the same Jesus who gave himself freely, the same Jesus who trusted the Father with everything is still giving grace, patiently, abundantly and without coercion.

17:57.633 --> 18:07.026
So if you leave today with anything, let it be this, you are not being pressured, you're being invited, invited to receive again,

18:07.266 --> 18:19.282
his grace anew, invited to trust in him again, and invited to discover that grace, when it's truly received, always finds a way to be shared.

